<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920310-0037</DOCNO><DOCID>920310-0037.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Business Records Corp.:   Net Is Revised After SEC   Queries Accounting Style</HL><DATE>03/10/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   BRCP</CO><MS>INDUSTRIAL (IDU)</MS><IN>ACCOUNTING (ACC)EARNINGS (ERN)INDUSTRIAL andamp; COMMERCIAL SERVICES (ICS)INDUSTRIAL AND COMMERCIAL SERVICES (SVC)</IN><NS>ACCOUNTING NEWS (ACC)EARNINGS (ERN)</NS><GV>SECURITIES AND EXCHANGE COMMISSION (SEC)</GV><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)TEXAS (TX)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Business Records Corp. restated its earnings, reducing its1991 net income to about $6 million, or $1.24 a share, andincreasing its 1990 net to $9.1 million, or $1.86 a share,after the Securities and Exchange Commission questioned itsefforts to smooth out the differences in its business betweenelection and non-election years.   The Dallas company, which provides election systems andservices to local governments, began in 1990 to record duringelection years the increased employee costs during electionyears as well as the cost of maintaining employees duringnonelection years. Business Records said its auditor,Deloitte andamp; Touche, concurred with the effort and concludedthat the company prepared its results in accordance withaccepted accouting practices.</LP><TEXT>   However, the company said the SEC's corporate financedivision reviewed the change and concluded that there weren'tany other companies that experienced such a two-year cycleand matched expenses in such a way.</TEXT></DOC>